The Telegraph - Calcutta : Opinion
Archives
				 In quest of the newSatish Gujral is arguably a better architect than an artist, though he is more renowned as the latter. His architectural designs have a great sense of geometry (Jindal farmhouse, top right). The same cannot be said of Gujrals paintings and drawings. Their forms and colours are far too voluptuous  even when the subject or theme does not warrant excesses  to follow linear discipline of any kind. SATISH GUJRAL: AN ARTOGRAPHY (Roli, Rs 3,500), is a killingly heavy tome, published to coincide with his retrospective at the National Gallery of Modern Art, New Delhi. It carries reproductions of his works  mural-like paintings with sweeping strokes, portraits, stylized drawings (bottom right), technicolor collages (left), pretentious burnt wood and metal sculptures, pastiche figures inspired by myths and a melodramatic and decorative reading of modern art movements. 
